commentBody:
@Barry Ancona
It is always good to remember that the commenters here are not representative of the puzzle solving population at large. 

I think the visual hints were a good idea.

@Barry Ancona 

Once I understood the trick, it helped a lot.  Because I was wondering what they were there for and why I got AREA FIFTY ONE, instead of area codes. 

I’d take this format over a rebus any day.

@Barry Ancona Agree it made it far too easy. After initially seeing that SWEET SPOT didn't fit, the crosses made it clear that it was SWEET SIXTEEN, which I just assumed was an Americanism for the sweet part of a baseball bat.

Then noticing that 16 was highlighted, I went ahead and wrote in TWENTY TWO and FIFTY ONE to the other theme answers, and eventually completed the other themes without even looking at their clues, thus completely missing the trick!

Bit of a shame.

@Joya 

Joya, you have the right attitude. And you can't go wrong with Deb as a guide to a puzzle's delights. I've enjoyed your comments and your spirit this last year...I hope you plunk down some choice(s) for Puzzle of the Year when I next solicit nominations!

(Same goes for the rest of y'all)

@Gary

Ha!

Tuba was just an answer the other day so I figured it was going to be tuba again even though I also thought more of a bass drum for the sound.

@Pani Korunova 
Now, you're going to be telling us that SAO means something different than SÃO in Portuguese--something naughty!

:-)

@Andrzej
The spelling in the clue is consistent with the rest of the newspaper.  More accurately, it is a transliteration.  For example, you will see “Swiatek” in the sports section.  

How would you suggest that the NYT present Russian, Arabic or Hebrew names?

@Tom S. 

Polish uses the same Latin alphabet as English so your Arabic, Hebrew or Russian examples don't work. We just add specific diacritics to Latin letters: they feature on any electronic keyboard. A few days ago résumé was spelled correctly so the NYT can do it right if they want to. 

The consistent misspelling of the name in the whole paper makes the case worse, not better.

@Pani Korunova 

I understand the simplification in the answers, but why does it feature in the clues too? If résumé can be spelled correctly, why not Świątek? Is a random word more worthy of being spelled correctly than the name of a living person?

Sooo... what exactly are the rules about misspelling foreign names in English? Losing the diacritics is OK, apparently. What about spelling D'Angelo without the '? DAngelo is ok? If it's not, how is Swiatek different?

@Andrzej 

Have you written to the editors about this? Though I'm not well versed as you and others, I think getting people's names right is the very most basic level of respect we can give.  

Worth writing them if you haven't.

@HeathieJ 

The last time I wrote to the NYT I did not even get a reply. The diacritics in my surname can't possibly have had anything to do with how I was treated, could they?

@Hanson
Ye gods, you got us! Well, you got *me*

@Andrzej 
Likewise on the matching PJS here in Scotland. I resisted the answer for quite a long time, because it seemed disconcerting enough to be that first unsettling moment in a horror film:
"Woah! They all have matching pyjamas! DO NOT SPEND THE NIGHT HERE!!!"

@dutchiris 

Well there’s a nice little meditative nugget.  When a cylindrical bat hits a spherical ball at an intersection where their diameters meet along the same hypothetical plane through which both moving objects are passing at the moment of impact, are they connecting at the sweet spot of the bat or the ball?  (It’s both, I guess.) 

But, since the bat is what’s in your hand and in your control, and a perfect connection leads to that sweet, sweet feeling of no vibration of the bat, just pure pop, it’s natural to think, “there, I found the sweet spot in the bat.”

@Warren 
Seems there are a lot of folks who have spent  considerable time and energy attempting to describe the meaning of the SWEET SPOT. Here’s one good example:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/fcpcfpzs" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/fcpcfpzs</a>

@Hardroch 

Should have realized that would be out there.  But they only analyzed half of the real world story by having the bat stationary and hitting it straight on with a hammer.  And referencing a “30 inch Little League *wood* bat”? In what century?

But thanks.

@Mike 
You're da bomb!  This one will make your "Greatest  Hits" collection.

Some peanuts and crackerjack for the emus...

@Vaer 

Unrelated, but I wanted to thank you for your song link yesterday.  I hadn't listened to them in a while, but played a large chunk of my XTC collection yesterday as a result of your post.  

So much music, so little time, so it's nice to get reminders like that.

@Vaer 

I got it from here

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2024/upshot/connections-bot.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2024/upshot/connections-bot.html</a>

@Nancy J. 

Different, yes. 

Delightful, not so much. After making three mistakes, I got a hint from some website that allowed me to see purple. I had the right idea for blue, but misinterpreted one of the drawings.

@Bill 

It was apple.  It was good.  It was the second of three apple pies we were given for Thanksgiving.  The one we put out was homemade.  We froze the other two.  This second one was quite good as well.

If you head to NY now, that third pie might be thawed out by then...

@Steve L 

I've always admired your crossword prowess but now even more so, I admire at your prioritization skills!! 

Mmm, pie!

@David Connell 

I don't object to languages having their own versions of place names, of course, or even the names of people. In Polish we used to polonize foreign proper names for centuries, and thus Paris became Paryż and Washington became Waszyngton. However, these days we no longer do that. Biden is Biden, not Bajden, as his name would have been styled over here had he lived one or two centuries ago. Trump would have been Tramp BTW.

I wouldn't mind seeing some phonetic version of Iga Świątek's name - at least that would make some sense and serve some purpose (Shvee-ohn-tech?). Skipping the diacritics in her Polish name, while the easiest thing to do, does nothing to inform people how to pronounce it, or even what her name really is (because it's Świątek, not Swiatek). It's just an error, and as correct as writing down Biden as Binde. I get it that's it not as easy to use the diacritics as it is to skip them, but is that a good enough reason to garble a living person's name?

@Jane

Correction to my longer post.
NBA is the National Basketball Association, the professional league, not team.

@Sheila Morris 
Thanks. I was confused by the fact that eg SWEET SIXTEEN and the other similar solutions are not the answers to any clues but only point somewhere else. 
Slang is constantly on the move. People in the US are particularly good at it! There are also lots of snappy abbreviations, which I don't think we do so much in the UK.

@Vaer 
I just open the NYT puzzle page and tap Print in the upper right corner.  I slmosr typed Left.
You can see, it is a struggle.

@Elyse G 
I'm only a solver of about 5 weeks, not 50 years, but I can see your point - the early week crosswords seem to be simply synonyms, which is gratifying for me at this stage, since it is the great NYT! 
The difficulties for me are over trivia - TV, sport and brand names of cakes etc and slang. I think a good clue involves some thought about the words and their intrinsic meanings.

@Travis - Only n00bs or Newbs wrote n00bs or Newbs.
Real XWorders wrote N—BS and waited for the crossings.

N00b alert!

@Bill 
Actually, if  you're 1337, it's n00bz.

(That's LEET, by the way, slang for elite. No, I was never a H4x0r.)
